<article>
    <h1>Black&#xAD;pink get flak for &#x2018;mis&#xAD;han&#xAD;dling&#x2019; baby panda</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201107/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-07"><time>2020-11-07</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE TRENDING</span>
        - <span role="byline">Lim Ruey Yan</span>
    </section>

    <p>Black­pink have sparked a con­tro­versy on Chi­nese so­cial me­dia for touch­ing a baby panda with their make-up on.</p>
    <p>On Wed­nes­day, the pop­u­lar Kpop girl group re­leased the trailer for the last episode of their re­al­ity show, 24/365 With Black­pink, which is sched­uled to be aired to­day.</p>
    <p>In the clip, Black­pink – com­pris­ing Jisoo, Jen­nie, Rose and Lisa – were seen go­ing to a theme park in Seoul to visit Fu Bao, the first panda to be born in South Korea about three months ago.</p>
    <p>Al­though Black­pink’s four mem­bers wore face masks, gloves and pro­tec­tive suits dur­ing their in­ter­ac­tion with the baby panda, their make-up riled ne­ti­zens in China.</p>
    <p>They said the make-up might cause ir­ri­ta­tion to the baby panda due to its low im­mu­nity and stressed that in China, only zookeep­ers are al­lowed to touch the pan­das to re­duce the pos­si­bil­ity of in­fec­tion and un­in­ten­tional harm.</p>
    <p>Some ne­ti­zens also pointed out that Lisa, 23, and Jisoo, 25, did not wear face masks while pre­par­ing food, while oth­ers pointed out that Jen­nie, 24, and Rose, 23, did not wear face masks and gloves while touch­ing the mother panda’s palm.</p>
    <p>How­ever, some South Korean fans claimed that rules in China do not ap­ply in South Korea.</p>
    <p>The theme park also said the Black­pink mem­bers fol­lowed the zookeep­ers’ in­struc­tions and sani­tised their hands dur­ing the record­ing.</p>

